Hey there, welcome to the Paws at Data Science Hangout. I'm Libby Herron, and this is a recording

00:00:16.600 --> 00:00:21.980
of our weekly community call that happens every Thursday at 12 p.m. U.S. Eastern Time.

00:00:21.980 --> 00:00:27.219
If you are not joining us live, you miss out on the amazing chat that's going on. So find

00:00:27.219 --> 00:00:30.660
the link in the description where you can add our call to your calendar and come hang

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:36.299
out with the most supportive, friendly, and funny data community you'll ever experience.

00:00:36.299 --> 00:00:38.180
Can't wait to see you there.

00:00:38.180 --> 00:00:44.939
I am so excited to introduce our featured leader today. It's Lisa Elkin, Senior Principal

00:00:44.939 --> 00:00:51.459
Computational Toxicologist at Pfizer. Lisa, your title is a mouthful. Thank you for joining

00:00:51.459 --> 00:00:56.939
us. I would love it if you could introduce yourself. Tell us a little bit about you and

00:00:56.939 --> 00:00:57.939
what you do.

00:00:57.939 --> 00:01:06.860
Sure. So I like to call myself a scientist turned data scientist. My background is in

00:01:06.860 --> 00:01:13.820
cell biology and biochemistry, and I spent about 20 years in the lab, most of that in

00:01:13.820 --> 00:01:18.860
the pharmaceutical industry in drug discovery. For those of you in the industry, I was in

00:01:18.860 --> 00:01:24.519
high throughput screening and hit assessment, which basically is like screening millions

00:01:24.519 --> 00:01:29.419
of molecules against a potential drug target of interest, and then working with programs

00:01:29.419 --> 00:01:37.160
to work with similar molecules to try and find a hit that can become a lead. So that's

00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:44.440
a really, really data rich area within drug discovery. And, you know, throughout my time

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:51.080
in the lab, I always really enjoyed working with data. I love doing big experiments where

00:01:51.080 --> 00:01:57.239
I could just like amass a huge quantity of data to sit with for a while. And while I

00:01:57.239 --> 00:02:03.480
was in the lab, I had some really great opportunities to learn more data analytics as a part of

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:11.399
my day job, both in training and working on projects. And then probably about eight years

00:02:11.399 --> 00:02:17.800
ago when my company closed their site, the site where I worked, I decided rather than

00:02:17.800 --> 00:02:23.720
relocate, I would reinvent myself as a data scientist. So that's what led me to my full

00:02:23.720 --> 00:02:32.440
time role here at Pfizer. And now I build applications to make scientists' lives easier.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:36.720
I love it. And tell us something that you like to do for fun outside of work.

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:44.000
For fun. I recently started Pilates this year, which I really like. Yeah, I love it.

00:02:44.399 --> 00:02:50.479
Oh, my gosh. Any other Pilates people in the chat? Let me know. I look at Pilates videos and feel fear.

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:58.479
It's just amazing for your core. I didn't remember I had a core until this year.

00:02:59.279 --> 00:03:04.720
Oh, my goodness. Rachel says the hardest workout I've ever done. Yeah, I have a cousin who does

00:03:04.720 --> 00:03:12.800
Pilates and it's intense. All right. Well, I would love to give everybody a little bit of

00:03:12.800 --> 00:03:17.919
context building stuff for our questions so that we can ask Lisa amazing questions.

00:03:18.880 --> 00:03:23.679
And so I wanted to just throw some topics out, some topics that I know

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:31.440
Lisa would be great to ask about. One is her career journey, just the non-traditional,

00:03:32.399 --> 00:03:38.800
non-data science stats background, ending up in full-time data science. Another one is

00:03:39.759 --> 00:03:46.559
growing inside of your role, whatever your role is right now, into a data science role, getting

00:03:46.559 --> 00:03:51.839
experience for data, how to advocate that to your boss, maybe how to find other places to

00:03:51.839 --> 00:03:55.520
get data into your role. That would be a great thing to talk with Lisa about.

00:03:57.279 --> 00:04:02.639
Another thing is being a tool builder. I love tools too. I am very tool focused.

00:04:03.279 --> 00:04:09.360
And so being a person who gets to build tools is very interesting to me and I know to Lisa as well.

00:04:10.479 --> 00:04:14.639
There are also a couple of things that I know I would love to talk with Lisa about, like

00:04:15.759 --> 00:04:22.880
upskilling inside of an organization systematically, right? Like setting up

00:04:22.880 --> 00:04:30.480
processes and structures to help people upskill into data literacy and adding more data to their

00:04:30.480 --> 00:04:38.399
roles or becoming analysts. And then also knowing when to use AI and when to not use AI is another

00:04:38.399 --> 00:04:45.760
great topic that we've been talking about. We talked about this with Jenny Bryan as well.

00:04:45.760 --> 00:04:52.160
All right, so let's get started with a couple of things here. I wanted to ask you a little bit

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:58.959
about what toxicology is because you have this very long word in your title and I don't understand

00:04:58.959 --> 00:05:06.000
100% what toxicology is. Yeah, so I work in preclinical drug safety in Pfizer.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:13.679
So this is basically early in drug discovery, we want to put the best molecules forward into the

00:05:13.679 --> 00:05:19.839
clinic. And so early in drug discovery, we're really trying to understand the potential safety

00:05:19.839 --> 00:05:24.799
liabilities. So it kind of starts very early. You pick a drug target and you try to understand like,

00:05:24.799 --> 00:05:31.279
all right, if we want to hit this particular enzyme or activate something, we want to

00:05:31.279 --> 00:05:38.799
understand what the potential safety liabilities are of doing that. So it

00:05:38.799 --> 00:05:44.799
comes down to sort of like researching what's out there. And then we do things like screen against

00:05:44.799 --> 00:05:51.600
known potential liabilities. So for example, we know certain small molecule drugs can affect

00:05:51.600 --> 00:05:56.880
ion channels in your heart. So we'll screen against those ion channels to make sure early

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:02.559
on in a program, you're not putting forward a molecule that we know hits these ion channels,

00:06:02.559 --> 00:06:08.640
right? Things like that. All the way to what happens in animal studies

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:19.440
when you expose an animal to a particular molecule. Okay, so just to like help my own brain,

00:06:19.440 --> 00:06:26.239
what are the data types that people like your tool users are interfacing with? Yeah, a lot of

00:06:26.239 --> 00:06:30.480
different data types. And that's one of the reasons I love my job so much is I get to flex all over

00:06:30.480 --> 00:06:35.760
the place to different types of data. In the early target space, it's literature mining. We actually

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:43.200
just built a tool that has an AI component that goes and pulls information from various pieces

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:51.679
of literature. It's early screening data is running assays on instrumentations that dump

00:06:51.679 --> 00:06:58.799
out a file and you need to translate the numbers in that instrument output into some sort of potency

00:06:58.799 --> 00:07:04.160
determination. How potent is my compound against this particular ion channel in your heart?

00:07:05.839 --> 00:07:12.959
All the way to, in animal studies, there's lots of different data to measure to see how

00:07:12.959 --> 00:07:20.720
the animals are responding to treatment. Awesome. That is very, very helpful. I feel like I see and

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:27.040
hear the word assay a lot in biostats and I don't 100% know what an assay is either.

00:07:27.679 --> 00:07:34.079
An assay is like a test. It's sort of like you have like a teeny tiny little test tube.

00:07:34.079 --> 00:07:38.399
Now they're very small. You might think of a test tube as this big thing, but they can teeny tiny

00:07:38.399 --> 00:07:44.720
little test tube. You put a compound in, you put something you're testing like a cell or an enzyme

00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:49.760
or something like that. Then you watch to see what that compound does to the enzyme.

00:07:50.399 --> 00:07:56.640
Okay. Awesome. Thank you so much. Well, I have a great question that popped up in Slido from

00:07:56.640 --> 00:08:03.679
Noor. Noor, if you're available, could you ask that one live? Hello. Sure. I love asking things live.

00:08:03.679 --> 00:08:08.959
Ask also, hi, a fellow computationalist, because I am a computational biologist slash biopharmacist

00:08:08.959 --> 00:08:15.359
actually trying to move into data science. This is actually tangentially related, but my question is,

00:08:15.359 --> 00:08:22.399
how do you think your science background benefits you as a data scientist? How do you think it can

00:08:23.279 --> 00:08:28.480
disadvantage you slash be in conflict with data science approaches? Because everyone says

00:08:28.480 --> 00:08:34.239
scientists are like, oh, so data science is like, not exactly. Right. For the longest time,

00:08:35.200 --> 00:08:40.320
when I got this role as a data scientist, originally my title was data scientist and

00:08:40.320 --> 00:08:45.200
moved to computational scientist. I didn't want to put it in LinkedIn because I would get all

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:49.760
sorts of requests. I'm like, well, I'm really a scientist. I don't want to call myself a data

00:08:49.760 --> 00:08:58.719
scientist yet because I'm not ready. I think being a scientist in the job that I have is

00:09:00.159 --> 00:09:07.280
really an advantage. I think that's the strongest thing that I can bring to the table is that

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:12.479
I understand what these scientists need. I know how they want to look at their data.

00:09:13.039 --> 00:09:22.000
I was there once 10, 15 years ago. I didn't know what a relational database was.

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:29.440
I can understand what is going to confuse them and what works with the way that they think.

00:09:30.239 --> 00:09:33.520
Because I know the way that they think, I can build tools that work

00:09:34.880 --> 00:09:41.599
that way, that aren't overwhelming, that think the way that they think. I think that's what I

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:48.320
bring to the table most. My data science skills, I'm rapidly trying to bring up to speed.

00:09:51.599 --> 00:09:54.479
Yeah. I think that's it. Go ahead.

00:09:54.479 --> 00:09:55.359
Was that good? Yeah.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:02.000
I think that's a great answer. I see you're nodding. This also brings up the topic of

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.840
imposter syndrome. We're dancing around this. I don't really love the term imposter syndrome,

00:10:07.840 --> 00:10:12.799
but it's what everybody identifies as. I call it unnecessary feelings of inadequacy,

00:10:12.799 --> 00:10:17.200
because you're a very smart and accomplished person, and yet you have this thing eating at

00:10:17.200 --> 00:10:24.719
you telling you that you're not adequate. I'm going to put a poll in the chat, actually.

00:10:25.760 --> 00:10:32.239
I think that was the second part of the question, was where are the disadvantages?

00:10:33.039 --> 00:10:35.520
Yeah. I don't know disadvantages,

00:10:35.520 --> 00:10:41.520
but I don't have the formal training that some of the data scientists have on my team.

00:10:42.559 --> 00:10:48.719
I'm not sure if I'm actually an imposter or I have imposter syndrome, but sometimes I feel like,

00:10:49.599 --> 00:10:54.559
wow, compared to these guys, what can I bring to the table? I think everybody in our team

00:10:54.559 --> 00:11:04.239
brings something to the role. We have a mix of... Most of the team has a background in biology,

00:11:04.239 --> 00:11:08.159
but some are much stronger in data science than others. I think we all bring something to the

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:19.280
table. I guess I bring 20 years of experience in the lab in different roles. I'm hoping that

00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:27.919
helps. People are often very happy with what I give them in terms of tools. I guess I have,

00:11:27.919 --> 00:11:34.000
but I do have imposter syndrome. But I'm not immune. I'm great, but I'm not immune.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:41.919
Yeah. I think that being a person who has had to use the tools, especially when the tools were not

00:11:41.919 --> 00:11:47.599
as good, makes you the best person to build the tools, because then you can advocate for the users

00:11:47.599 --> 00:11:53.599
in a way that somebody who's coming in and who's superficially learning about end user processes

00:11:53.599 --> 00:11:59.039
could never, because they've never been in the trenches and suffering the way that you have

00:11:59.679 --> 00:12:06.320
or frustrated. That was a great question, Nora. Thanks for asking. I am looking at our poll,

00:12:06.320 --> 00:12:13.440
do you feel imposter syndrome or feeling of inadequacy? The vast majority of us so far

00:12:13.520 --> 00:12:19.359
absolutely feel imposter syndrome. Whether we have a background in stats and data or we don't

00:12:19.359 --> 00:12:24.400
have a background in stats or data, the majority of us are saying, yep, I still have imposter

00:12:24.400 --> 00:12:32.239
syndrome. Good to know. That makes me feel better. Yeah. We're not alone. While we're at it,

00:12:33.039 --> 00:12:40.799
let's ask another question, which is, do you even have a traditional background? Where are we all?

00:12:40.799 --> 00:12:45.119
Are we traditional background people or nontraditional? I think I'm nontraditional.

00:12:45.119 --> 00:12:51.200
Lisa, you think so too, right? Yeah. Nontraditional. Yeah, I did not have

00:12:52.880 --> 00:13:00.320
the background. When I was in college and I took a stats class where you had to program,

00:13:00.320 --> 00:13:04.080
you had to go to the mainframe lab to do any programming.

00:13:04.239 --> 00:13:13.359
That's how. Like I said, I didn't know what a relational database was not too long ago.

00:13:13.359 --> 00:13:16.559
There are probably people in the chat who do not know what mainframe is even.

00:13:17.919 --> 00:13:20.080
You have to go to a room with computers.

00:13:22.960 --> 00:13:27.919
I have worked for companies in the past decade who still operate some of their stuff on mainframe,

00:13:27.919 --> 00:13:34.880
so it's not gone. Lisa, do you want to explain mainframe a little bit? Actually, this might be.

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:42.159
All I know is that we didn't really have personal computers. We just had personal computers where

00:13:42.159 --> 00:13:49.919
you stick one of those floppy floppy disks into the thing. There wasn't coding without going

00:13:49.919 --> 00:13:55.599
somewhere that had the compute power to support that. It's like an enormous computer in a

00:13:55.599 --> 00:14:01.679
centralized location that everyone needs to go to in order to access or operate.

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:07.200
Not exactly as a supercomputer, but computers also had to be a lot bigger

00:14:08.080 --> 00:14:12.479
back then than they do now. Computers can be a lot smaller. Our compute has gotten

00:14:12.479 --> 00:14:19.039
bigger and smaller at the same time, which means that 20 or 30 years ago, it was huge and a lot

00:14:19.039 --> 00:14:24.559
slower. There are probably going to be some mainframe descriptions that are better than

00:14:24.559 --> 00:14:28.880
mine in the chat right now. Hopefully, somebody will walk us through that in the chat.

00:14:30.479 --> 00:14:33.200
Thank you, thank you, thank you. It looks like our poll on,

00:14:33.200 --> 00:14:37.760
are you traditional or nontraditional? More nontraditional than traditional.

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:42.960
I'm considering myself nontraditional, even though I have two degrees that are data-focused.

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:48.239
I didn't get to do that until I was in my 30s, so definitely a winding path.

00:14:49.200 --> 00:14:54.000
All right, let's head over to our questions, because I see that Dami asked one about

00:14:54.640 --> 00:14:57.919
Shiny apps. Dami, would you be available to ask that live?

00:14:59.039 --> 00:14:59.599
Of course.

00:15:00.239 --> 00:15:01.039
Hey, Dami.

00:15:01.039 --> 00:15:01.359
Hey.

00:15:01.359 --> 00:15:02.159
Hi, Dami.

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:07.520
Hi. Hi, Lisa. I know you build a lot of Shiny apps for your work, and I was just wondering,

00:15:07.520 --> 00:15:11.919
what kind of audience do you build it for, and what is your workflow, your thought process

00:15:11.919 --> 00:15:12.719
when building one?

00:15:13.679 --> 00:15:24.799
Yeah. Mostly for scientists, but different kinds of scientists. In vitro scientists who work

00:15:24.799 --> 00:15:31.359
with assays in TestTube, they're used to a lot of data. They tend to have to do some data analysis

00:15:31.359 --> 00:15:40.479
themselves. That's one person that I work with. They're pretty data-savvy, but they don't know

00:15:40.479 --> 00:15:49.200
how to build an application that's going to automate analysis for them. In that case,

00:15:51.039 --> 00:15:58.479
those apps that I've built, I rely heavily on my experience as a scientist and what are the steps

00:15:58.479 --> 00:16:06.559
that I use to analyze that data, and what do they want to see? I think about it in terms of a

00:16:06.559 --> 00:16:16.159
workflow. Some of the apps that I build, I'm learning to build modular Shiny apps. I am still

00:16:16.159 --> 00:16:27.840
learning, but I like that approach because I can pick and choose different modules depending on

00:16:27.840 --> 00:16:38.080
the situation. I can reuse modules potentially. A lot of the planning just happens in my head.

00:16:38.080 --> 00:16:46.479
I know you should write things down and map things out in terms of what you want to do.

00:16:48.159 --> 00:16:53.359
So far, sometimes I keep that in my head. Occasionally, I have mapped data flows,

00:16:54.080 --> 00:16:59.440
like, and I don't use anything fancy. I'll grab a PowerPoint and sort of like, all right, where are

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:05.040
my data sources? Where are they coming from? What are the steps and the data transformations that I

00:17:05.040 --> 00:17:11.199
need to do? Sometimes I do that just to explain what I'm trying to do to other people, other

00:17:11.199 --> 00:17:16.880
technical users. Sometimes we've collaborated with outside vendors on particular projects,

00:17:16.959 --> 00:17:22.160
and in that case, it really helps a lot is sort of just mapping out the data flow.

00:17:23.439 --> 00:17:30.160
Yeah. Anybody else pencil and paper their first step to anything? That's me, mapping out everything.

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:38.319
Yeah, I do do a lot of scribbles. Yes. I have aspirations to keep a really nice notebook,

00:17:39.280 --> 00:17:46.000
and I tend to just do a lot on scrap paper and doodle at the same time.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:50.160
Marlene is holding her notebook up. I'm like, yeah, let me just hold my pile of scribbled

00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:54.959
stickies up for you because I can't operate without them. Great question, Dami. Thank you

00:17:54.959 --> 00:18:01.680
for asking, and let's head over to Slido and find another question. I see one from Cecilia,

00:18:01.680 --> 00:18:06.640
and it's got an asterisk next to it. That means, hey, let me read this for me. So I will read

00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:12.319
from Cecilia Bartoli. What made you decide to switch to industry? What were the bottlenecks

00:18:12.319 --> 00:18:18.959
in your understanding between academia and industry? Yeah. Okay, so this was a long time ago,

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:31.839
but when I was in my probably second year of my postdoc, I always thought that I would go

00:18:31.839 --> 00:18:36.560
into academia, that I would be a professor somewhere. My mother was a professor. That's

00:18:36.560 --> 00:18:44.560
the life that I knew, but I realized I would kind of have to move all over the country

00:18:44.560 --> 00:18:54.239
in order to go where the jobs were, and so at the same time, there was sort of a biotech boom

00:18:55.839 --> 00:19:04.000
out in New Haven, Connecticut near Yale, and there was a professor who was starting up a biotech,

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:11.520
and I joined that just thinking, well, I'll see what it's like. In retrospect,

00:19:12.239 --> 00:19:18.800
over the last 20 years, I realized, wow, I am actually much more suited to industry

00:19:19.599 --> 00:19:26.880
than academia. First, because I really like variety. I get bored. There are people I postdoc

00:19:26.880 --> 00:19:31.760
with who still study the same molecules that they studied 20 years ago. I'm like, I can't believe

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:38.079
that. Maybe I don't have the attention span. I think I tend to be like a jack of all trades

00:19:38.079 --> 00:19:46.079
rather than master of anything, and I find that in the pharmaceutical industry, there's

00:19:46.079 --> 00:19:56.000
a lot of different variety. There's the ability to move around. You're very goal-focused. It's

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:04.160
very practical, and I feel like that suits me, and I'm also very process-oriented, just like in

00:20:04.160 --> 00:20:10.000
building tools. It's sort of like, how are you doing this process? Is it efficient? Are you

00:20:10.640 --> 00:20:16.959
walking back and forth across the lab? Do you have to transfer a USB stick from one computer

00:20:16.959 --> 00:20:22.400
to the other? Are you copying and pasting into Excel? That all sort of like, for some reason,

00:20:23.040 --> 00:20:28.719
that suits me the way that I think, and my sort of drive to

00:20:30.640 --> 00:20:38.079
fix broken processes. That's very fair. The question, what are the gaps?

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:48.719
I feel like because I went into a small biotech company, I kind of learned on the job.

00:20:49.680 --> 00:20:55.599
You have to get used to a lot of meanings, but that didn't happen right away.

00:20:55.599 --> 00:21:01.680
That wasn't at biotech. That was mostly pharma, and carving out time for yourself to think

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:06.479
and to continue to learn. We talked about this a little bit, Libby, is

00:21:07.359 --> 00:21:15.040
continuing to grow and upskill while you are doing your day job.

00:21:18.400 --> 00:21:26.959
That has really helped me get where I am, even moving from the lab to data science.

00:21:28.400 --> 00:21:34.640
I love learning. I'm not happy if I'm not learning, basically, but carving out that time

00:21:34.640 --> 00:21:41.839
can sometimes be hard. I had some really great opportunities, both at the last company I worked

00:21:41.839 --> 00:21:52.239
with, Bristol-Myers Squibb, and this company at Pfizer, in joining programs that were

00:21:54.239 --> 00:22:00.079
enterprise-wide programs for learning. When I was at Bristol-Myers Squibb and I was still

00:22:00.079 --> 00:22:09.280
working in the lab, I had the opportunity to work with a group called the

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:15.920
Analytics Exchange, which was basically a program you could apply to where you would learn data

00:22:15.920 --> 00:22:23.599
science skills, but also work on projects. People from across the company, from commercial

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:31.199
to clinical to manufacturing, would submit little projects, little analytics projects,

00:22:31.839 --> 00:22:37.520
a challenge that they had. Basically, different teams on this Analytics Exchange could work on

00:22:38.719 --> 00:22:46.959
those projects and learn by doing. That was my real entry point into data science.

00:22:47.439 --> 00:22:57.599
So, as a part of that project, your manager had to approve your participation in the Analytics

00:22:57.599 --> 00:23:04.000
Exchange and carve out 20% of your time to do that. You're not always that lucky.

00:23:06.079 --> 00:23:12.719
At Pfizer, we have something similar. There's a large-scale enterprise-wide program, and there's

00:23:12.719 --> 00:23:22.319
also a smaller-scale program where I really learned R beyond what I had done previously.

